></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p><b>Goldbach's conjecture</b> is one of the oldest and best-known <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_unsolved_problems_in_mathematics"=
 title=3D"List of unsolved problems in mathematics">unsolved problems</a> i=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory" title=3D"Number t=
heory">number theory</a> and all of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathematics">mathematics</a>. It states that every =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Even_and_odd_numbers" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Even and odd numbers">even</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Natural_number" title=3D"Natural number">natural number</a>=
 greater than 2 is the sum of two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Prime_number" title=3D"Prime number">prime numbers</a>.
</p><p>The conjecture has been shown to hold for all natural numbers less t=
han <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7018400000000000000=E2=
=99=A0"></span>4<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=
=97</span>10<sup>18</sup></span>, but remains unproven despite considerable=
 effort.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGoldbach%27s_conjectur=
e&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Origins">Origins</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGoldbach%27s_conjectur=
e&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Origins"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>On 7 June 1742, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prussia" ti=
tle=3D"Prussia">Prussian</a> mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Christian_Goldbach" title=3D"Christian Goldbach">Christian Goldbac=
h</a> wrote a letter to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonhard_E=
uler" title=3D"Leonhard Euler">Leonhard Euler</a> (letter XLIII),<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G=
oldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> in which he proposed the fol=
lowing conjecture:
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>Every integer that can be written as=
 the sum of two primes can also be written as the sum of as many primes (in=
cluding unity) as one wishes, until all terms are units.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%2=
7s_conjecture#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p>Goldbach was following the now-abandoned convention of <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#Primality_of_one" title=3D"Prime numbe=
r">considering 1</a> to be a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime=
_number" title=3D"Prime number">prime number</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MathWo=
rldConj_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G=
oldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-MathWorldConj-4"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> so that a sum =
of units would be a sum of primes. He then proposed a second conjecture in =
the margin of his letter, which implies the first:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_con=
jecture#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>b<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1244412712"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>It seems at least, that =
every integer greater than 2 can be written as the sum of three primes.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>c<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p>Euler replied in a letter dated 30 June 1742<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjec=
ture#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and reminded Goldbach of an earlier conversati=
on they had had (<span title=3D"German-language text"><i lang=3D"de">"...&n=
bsp;so Ew. vormals mit mir communicirt haben&nbsp;..."</i></span>), in whic=
h Goldbach had remarked that the first of those two conjectures would follo=
w from the statement
</p>
<div class=3D"block-indent">Every positive even integer can be written as t=
he sum of two primes.</div>
<p>This is in fact equivalent to his second, marginal conjecture. In the le=
tter dated 30 June 1742, Euler stated:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-theorema_8-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conj=
ecture#cite_note-theorema-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-PrimeGlossary_9-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27=
s_conjecture#cite_note-PrimeGlossary-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1244412712"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>That&nbsp;... every even=
 integer is a sum of two primes, I regard as a completely certain theorem, =
although I cannot prove it.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-10">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>d<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup></p></blockquote>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Similar_conjecture_by_Desca=
rtes">Similar conjecture by Descartes</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DGoldbach%27s_conjecture&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sec=
tion=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Similar conjecture by Descartes"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Descartes" title=3D"R=
en=C3=A9 Descartes">Ren=C3=A9 Descartes</a> wrote, "Every even number can b=
e expressed as the sum of at most three primes."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conj=
ecture#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This proposition is similar to, but weaker =
than, Goldbach's conjecture. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_=
Erd%C5%91s" title=3D"Paul Erd=C5=91s">Paul Erd=C5=91s</a> said, "Descartes =
actually discovered this before Goldbach ... but it is better that the conj=
ecture was named for Goldbach because, mathematically speaking, Descartes w=
as infinitely rich and Goldbach was very poor."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conje=
cture#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Partial_results">Partial re=
sults</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGoldba=
ch%27s_conjecture&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Partial results"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<p>Goldbach's conjecture involving the sum of two primes is much more diffi=
cult than the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weak_Goldbach_conjec=
ture" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Weak Goldbach conjecture">weak Goldbac=
h conjecture</a>, which says that every odd integer greater than 5 is the s=
um of three primes. Using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivan_Vin=
ogradov#Mathematical_contributions" title=3D"Ivan Vinogradov">Vinogradov's =
method</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nikolai_Chudakov" titl=
e=3D"Nikolai Chudakov">Nikolai Chudakov</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjec=
ture#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joha=
nnes_van_der_Corput" title=3D"Johannes van der Corput">Johannes van der Cor=
put</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theodor_Estermann" title=3D"Theodor E=
stermann">Theodor Estermann</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-=
15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> showed (1937=E2=80=931938) that <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Almost_all" title=3D"Almost all">almost all</a> even numbers =
can be written as the sum of two primes (in the sense that the fraction of =
even numbers up to some <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">N</span> which can be so written tends towards 1 as <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N</span> increases). In 1930, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lev_Schnirelmann" title=3D"Lev Schnir=
elmann">Lev Schnirelmann</a> proved that any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Natural_number" title=3D"Natural number">natural number</a> grea=
ter than 1 can be written as the sum of not more than <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">C</span> prime numbers, where <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">C</span> is an effectivel=
y computable constant; see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schnire=
lmann_density" title=3D"Schnirelmann density">Schnirelmann density</a>.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%2=
7s_conjecture#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Schnirelmann's constant is the lowe=
st number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">C</span=
> with this property. Schnirelmann himself obtained <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>C</i> &lt; <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"700580000000=
0000000=E2=99=A0"></span>800<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">000</span></=
span></span>. This result was subsequently enhanced by many authors, such a=
s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olivier_Ramar%C3%A9" title=3D"Ol=
ivier Ramar=C3=A9">Olivier Ramar=C3=A9</a>, who in 1995 showed that every e=
ven number <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =E2=89=A5 4</span> is in fact t=
he sum of at most 6 primes. The best known result stems from the proof of t=
he weak Goldbach conjecture by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Har=
ald_Helfgott" title=3D"Harald Helfgott">Harald Helfgott</a>,<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldb=
ach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which directly implies that ev=
ery even number <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =E2=89=A5 4</span> is the =
sum of at most 4 primes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-19"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1924, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G._H._Hardy" title=
=3D"G. H. Hardy">Hardy</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joh=
n_Edensor_Littlewood" title=3D"John Edensor Littlewood">Littlewood</a> show=
ed under the assumption of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gen=
eralized_Riemann_hypothesis" title=3D"Generalized Riemann hypothesis">gener=
alized Riemann hypothesis</a> that the number of even numbers up to <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">X</span> violating the G=
oldbach conjecture is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inequality_(=
mathematics)" title=3D"Inequality (mathematics)">much less than</a> <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>X</i><sup><span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">1</s=
pan>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span> + <i>c</i></sup></span> fo=
r small <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"no=
print Inline-Template" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources#What_information_to_include=
" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citing sources"><span title=3D"A complete citation is =
needed. (June 2025)">full citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>In 1948, using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sieve_theory=
" title=3D"Sieve theory">sieve theory</a> methods, <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Alfr%C3%A9d_R%C3%A9nyi" title=3D"Alfr=C3=A9d R=C3=A9nyi">A=
lfr=C3=A9d R=C3=A9nyi</a> showed that every sufficiently large even number =
can be written as the sum of a prime and an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Almost_prime" title=3D"Almost prime">almost prime</a> with at mos=
t <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">K</span> factor=
s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Alfr=C3=A9d_R=C3=A9nyi_1948_22-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note=
-Alfr%C3%A9d_R%C3%A9nyi_1948-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Chen_Jingrun" title=3D"Chen Jingrun">Chen Jingrun</a> showed in =
1973 using sieve theory that every <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Sufficiently_large" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sufficiently large">suf=
ficiently large</a> even number can be written as the sum of either two pri=
mes, or a prime and a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semiprime" t=
itle=3D"Semiprime">semiprime</a> (the product of two primes).<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gold=
bach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> See <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Chen%27s_theorem" title=3D"Chen's theorem">Chen's theorem</=
a> for further information.
</p><p>In 1975, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugh_Lowell_Montgo=
mery" title=3D"Hugh Lowell Montgomery">Hugh Lowell Montgomery</a> and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bob_Vaughan" title=3D"Bob Vaughan">Bob =
Vaughan</a> showed that "most" even numbers are expressible as the sum of t=
wo primes. More precisely, they showed that there exist positive constants =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> and <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">C</span> such that fo=
r all sufficiently large numbers <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">N</span>, every even number less than <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N</span> is the sum of two primes, wit=
h at most <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>CN</i><sup>1 =E2=88=92 <i>c</i></sup><=
/span> exceptions. In particular, the set of even integers that are not the=
 sum of two primes has <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_den=
sity" title=3D"Natural density">density</a> zero.
</p><p>In 1951, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yuri_Linnik" title=
=3D"Yuri Linnik">Yuri Linnik</a> proved the existence of a constant <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">K</span> such that every=
 sufficiently large even number is the sum of two primes and at most <span =
class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">K</span> powers of 2. <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J%C3%A1nos_Pintz" title=3D"J=C3=A1n=
os Pintz">J=C3=A1nos Pintz</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Imre_Z._Ruzsa" title=3D"Imre Z. Ruzsa">Imre Ruzsa</a> found in 2020 that <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>K</i> =3D 8</span> works.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_c=
onjecture#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Assuming the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Generalized_Riemann_hypothesis" title=3D"Generalized Rieman=
n hypothesis">generalized Riemann hypothesis</a>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>K</i> =3D 7</span> also works, as shown by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Roger_Heath-Brown" title=3D"Roger Heath-Brown">Roger Heath-Brown=
</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DJan-Christ=
oph_Schlage-Puchta&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new" title=
=3D"Jan-Christoph Schlage-Puchta (page does not exist)">Jan-Christoph Schla=
ge-Puchta</a> in 2002.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-25"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p><p>In 2013, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harald_Helfgott" t=
itle=3D"Harald Helfgott">Harald Helfgott</a> submitted a proof of the weak =
conjecture to the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DAnnals_of_Mathematics_Studies&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=
=3D"new" title=3D"Annals of Mathematics Studies (page does not exist)">Anna=
ls of Mathematics Studies</a></i> book series. The article was accepted, bu=
t Helfgott decided to undertake major modifications suggested by the refere=
e. Despite several revisions, Helfgott's proof has not yet appeared in a pe=
er-reviewed publication.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Helfgott_2013_26-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#c=
ite_note-Helfgott_2013-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Helfgott_2012_27-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27=
s_conjecture#cite_note-Helfgott_2012-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-28"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_=
conjecture#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The weak conjecture is implied by the =
Goldbach conjecture, as if <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =E2=88=92 3</sp=
an> is a sum of two primes, then <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">n</span> is a sum of three primes. But the converse implica=
tion and thus the Goldbach conjecture remain unproven even if Helfgott's pr=
oof is correct.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Computational_results">Comp=
utational results</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DGoldbach%27s_conjecture&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"E=
dit section: Computational results"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>For small values of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">n</span>, the Goldbach conjecture (and hence the weak Goldbach conjec=
ture) can be verified directly. For instance, in 1938, Nils Pipping laborio=
usly verified the conjecture up to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =3D <sp=
an class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7005100000000000000=E2=99=A0">=
</span>100<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">000</span></span></span>.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> With the advent of c=
omputers, many more values of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">n</span> have been checked; T. Oliveira e Silva ran a distribu=
ted computer search that has verified the conjecture for <span class=3D"tex=
html"><i>n</i> =E2=89=A4 <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"70=
18400000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>4<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margi=
n-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>18</sup></span></span> (and double-che=
cked up to <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7017400000000000=
000=E2=99=A0"></span>4<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em=
;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>17</sup></span>) as of 2013. One record from this se=
arch is that <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"70183325581707=
33396=E2=99=A0"></span>3<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">325</span><span =
style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">581</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">7=
07</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">333</span><span style=3D"margin=
-left:.25em;">960</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">528</span></span=
> is the smallest number that cannot be written as a sum of two primes wher=
e one is smaller than 9781.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-30">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"In_popular_culture">In popu=
lar culture</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Goldbach%27s_conjecture&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: In popular culture"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><i>Goldbach's Conjecture</i> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T=
raditional_Chinese_characters" title=3D"Traditional Chinese characters">Chi=
nese</a>: <span lang=3D"zh-Hant">=E5=93=A5=E5=BE=B7=E5=B7=B4=E8=B5=AB=E7=8C=
=9C=E6=83=B3</span>) is the title of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Xu_Chi" title=3D"Xu Chi">Xu Chi</a>'s biography of Chinese mathematician=
 and number theorist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chen_Jingrun"=
 title=3D"Chen Jingrun">Chen Jingrun</a>.
</p><p>The conjecture is a central point in the plot of <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apostolos_Doxiadis" title=3D"Apostolos Doxiadis">Apos=
tolos Doxiadis</a>'s 1992 novel <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Uncle_Petros_and_Goldbach%27s_Conjecture" title=3D"Uncle Petros and Goldba=
ch's Conjecture">Uncle Petros and Goldbach's Conjecture</a></i>, in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Asimov" title=3D"Isaac Asimov">Isaa=
c Asimov</a>'s short story "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sixty_=
Million_Trillion_Combinations" title=3D"Sixty Million Trillion Combinations=
">Sixty Million Trillion Combinations</a>", and in <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Michelle_Richmond" title=3D"Michelle Richmond">Michelle Ri=
chmond</a>'s 2008 mystery novel <i>No One You Know</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%2=
7s_conjecture#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Goldbach's conjecture is part of the plot of the 2007 Spanish film <=
i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat%27s_Room" title=3D"Fermat=
's Room">Fermat's Room</a></i>.
</p><p>Goldbach's conjecture is featured as the main topic of research of t=
he eponymous character Marguerite in the 2023 French-Swiss film <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marguerite%27s_Theorem" title=3D"Margueri=
te's Theorem">Marguerite's Theorem</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjectur=
e#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Formal_statement">Formal st=
atement</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGold=
bach%27s_conjecture&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Formal statement"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Each of the three conjectures has a natural analog in terms of the moder=
n definition of a prime, under which 1 is excluded. A modern version of the=
 first conjecture is:
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
996643573"><div class=3D"block-indent">Every integer that can be written as=
 the sum of two primes can also be written as the sum of as many primes as =
one wishes, until either all terms are two (if the integer is even) or one =
term is three and all other terms are two (if the integer is odd).</div>
<p>A modern version of the marginal conjecture is:
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
996643573"><div class=3D"block-indent">Every integer greater than 5 can be =
written as the sum of three primes.</div>
<p>And a modern version of Goldbach's older conjecture of which Euler remin=
ded him is:
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
996643573"><div class=3D"block-indent"> Every even integer greater than 2 c=
an be written as the sum of two primes.</div>
<p>These modern versions might not be entirely equivalent to the correspond=
ing original statements. For example, if there were an even integer <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>N</i> =3D <i>p</i> + 1</span> larger than 4, for <span =
class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span> a prime, that =
could not be expressed as the sum of two primes in the modern sense, then i=
t would be a counterexample to the modern version of the third conjecture (=
without being a counterexample to the original version). The modern version=
 is thus probably stronger (but in order to confirm that, one would have to=
 prove that the first version, freely applied to any positive even integer =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>, could n=
ot possibly rule out the existence of such a specific counterexample <span =
class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N</span>). In any case,=
 the modern statements have the same relationships with each other as the o=
lder statements did. That is, the second and third modern statements are eq=
uivalent, and either implies the first modern statement.
</p><p>The third modern statement (equivalent to the second) is the form in=
 which the conjecture is usually expressed today. It is also known as the "=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_jargon#strong" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mathematical jargon">strong</a>", "even", or "bin=
ary" Goldbach conjecture. A weaker form of the second modern statement, kno=
wn as "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_weak_conjectur=
e" title=3D"Goldbach's weak conjecture">Goldbach's weak conjecture</a>", th=
e "odd Goldbach conjecture", or the "ternary Goldbach conjecture", asserts =
that=20
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
996643573"><div class=3D"block-indent">Every odd integer greater than 7 can=
 be written as the sum of three odd primes.</div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Heuristic_justification">He=
uristic justification</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DGoldbach%27s_conjecture&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=
=3D"Edit section: Heuristic justification"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Goldbach_partitions_of_the_ev=
en_integers_from_4_to_28_300px.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=
=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/dd/Goldbach_partitions=
_of_the_even_integers_from_4_to_28_300px.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"3=
00" height=3D"283" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"300" data-f=
ile-height=3D"283"></a><figcaption>Sums of two primes at the intersections =
of three lines</figcaption></figure>
<p>Statistical considerations that focus on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Prime_number_theorem" title=3D"Prime number theorem">probabil=
istic distribution of prime numbers</a> present informal evidence in favour=
 of the conjecture (in both the weak and strong forms) for <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sufficiently_large" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Sufficiently large">sufficiently large</a> integers: the greater the integ=
er, the more ways there are available for that number to be represented as =
the sum of two or three other numbers and the more "likely" it becomes that=
 at least one of these representations consists entirely of primes.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Goldbach-1000000.png" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/7/7c/Goldbach-1000000.png/330px-Goldbach-1000000.png" decodi=
ng=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=3D"210" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-fi=
le-width=3D"720" data-file-height=3D"504"></a><figcaption>Number of ways to=
 write an even number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">n</span> as the sum of two primes (sequence <span class=3D"nowrap exte=
rnal"><a href=3D"https://oeis.org/A002375" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"oeis:A0=
02375">A002375</a></span> in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/O=
n-Line_Encyclopedia_of_Integer_Sequences" title=3D"On-Line Encyclopedia of =
Integer Sequences">OEIS</a>)</figcaption></figure>
<p>A very crude version of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heu=
ristic" title=3D"Heuristic">heuristic</a> probabilistic argument (for the s=
trong form of the Goldbach conjecture) is as follows. The <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number_theorem" title=3D"Prime number theorem=
">prime number theorem</a> asserts that an integer <span class=3D"texhtml m=
var" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> selected at random has roughly a=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion=
"><span class=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=
=3D"den">ln <i>m</i></span></span>=E2=81=A0</span></span> chance of being p=
rime. Thus if <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</=
span> is a large even integer and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fon=
t-style:italic;">m</span> is a number between 3 and <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:=
r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span clas=
s=3D"num"><i>n</i></span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den=
">2</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span></span>, then one might expect the probabi=
lity of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> =
and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =E2=88=92 <i>m</i></span> simultaneous=
ly being prime to be <span class=3D"texhtml"><link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-i=
nline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfr=
ac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">1</span><span class=
=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">ln <i>m</i> ln(<i>n</i> =E2=88=92 =
<i>m</i>)</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span></span>. If one pursues this heurist=
ic, one might expect the total number of ways to write a large even integer=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> as the =
sum of two odd primes to be roughly
