<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Goldbach_partition_function=
">Goldbach partition function</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DGoldbach%27s_conjecture&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9=
" title=3D"Edit section: Goldbach partition function"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Goldbachs_comet.gif" class=3D"mw-file-descrip=
tion"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb=
/Goldbachs_comet.gif/330px-Goldbachs_comet.gif" decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"300" height=3D"223" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"388" data=
-file-height=3D"288"></a><figcaption>Goldbach's comet; red, blue and green =
points correspond respectively the values 0, 1 and 2 modulo 3 of the number=
.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <i><span class=3D"vanchor"><span id=3D"Goldbach_partition"></span><s=
pan class=3D"vanchor-text">Goldbach partition</span></span> function</i> as=
sociates to each even integer the number of ways it can be decomposed into =
a sum of two primes. Its graph looks like a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Comet" title=3D"Comet">comet</a> and is therefore called <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_comet" title=3D"Goldbach's c=
omet">Goldbach's comet</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-33">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p><p>Goldbach's comet suggests tight upper and lower bounds on the number=
 of representations of an even number as the sum of two primes, and also th=
at the number of these representations depends strongly on the value modulo=
 3 of the number.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Related_problems">Related p=
roblems</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGold=
bach%27s_conjecture&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Related problems"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Although Goldbach's conjecture implies that every positive integer great=
er than one can be written as a sum of at most three primes, it is not alwa=
ys possible to find such a sum using a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Greedy_algorithm" title=3D"Greedy algorithm">greedy algorithm</a> that=
 uses the largest possible prime at each step. The <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Pillai_sequence" title=3D"Pillai sequence">Pillai sequence=
</a> tracks the numbers requiring the largest number of primes in their gre=
edy representations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-34"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p><p>Similar problems to Goldbach's conjecture exist in which primes are =
replaced by other particular sets of numbers, such as the squares:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph-Louis_Lagrange" tit=
le=3D"Joseph-Louis Lagrange">Lagrange</a> proved that <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrange%27s_four-square_theorem" title=3D"Lagrange's f=
our-square theorem">every positive integer is the sum of four squares</a>. =
See <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waring%27s_problem" title=3D"W=
aring's problem">Waring's problem</a> and the related <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waring%E2%80%93Goldbach_problem" title=3D"Waring=E2=80=
=93Goldbach problem">Waring=E2=80=93Goldbach problem</a> on sums of powers =
of primes.</li>
<li>Hardy and Littlewood listed as their Conjecture I: "Every large odd num=
ber (<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> &gt; 5</span>) is the sum of a prime =
and the double of a prime".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-35">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> This conjecture is known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Lemoine%27s_conjecture" title=3D"Lemoine's conjecture">Lemoine's conj=
ecture</a> and is also called <i>Levy's conjecture</i>.</li>
<li>The Goldbach conjecture for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pr=
actical_number" title=3D"Practical number">practical numbers</a>, a prime-l=
ike sequence of integers, was stated by Margenstern in 1984,<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldb=
ach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and proved by <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giuseppe_Melfi" title=3D"Giuseppe Melfi">Melfi</a>=
 in 1996:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> every =
even number is a sum of two practical numbers.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harvey_Dubner" title=3D"Harvey=
 Dubner">Harvey Dubner</a> proposed a strengthening of the Goldbach conject=
ure: that every even integer greater than 4208 is the sum of two <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Twin_prime" title=3D"Twin prime">twin primes=
</a> (not necessarily belonging to the same pair).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_co=
njecture#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template n=
oprint noexcerpt Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:NOTRS" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Wikipedia:NOTRS"><span title=3D"This is raw html, although it seems =
to have been published in Recreational Mathematics (September 2023)">better=
&nbsp;source&nbsp;needed</span></a></i>]</sup> Only 34 even integers less t=
han 4208 are not the sum of two twin primes; Dubner has verified computatio=
nally that this list is complete up to <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-=
math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-=
a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/M=
athML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle 2\cdot 10^{10}.}">
