class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup><sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[=
<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title=
=3D"Wikipedia:Verifiability"><span title=3D"This source states 10^9, and th=
e other source is unclear on the limit (September 2023)">verification neede=
d</span></a></i>]</sup> A proof of this stronger conjecture would imply not=
 only Goldbach's conjecture but also the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Twin_prime_conjecture" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Twin prime con=
jecture">twin prime conjecture</a>.</li></ul>
<p>Goldbach's conjecture is used to study computational complexity.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-quanta_40-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-quanta-40"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  The c=
onnection is made through the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Busy=
_Beaver" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Busy Beaver">Busy Beaver</a> functi=
on, where BB(<i>n</i>) is the maximum number of steps taken by any <i>n</i>=
 state <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turing_machine" title=3D"Tu=
ring machine">Turing machine</a> that halts. There is a 27-state Turing mac=
hine that halts if and only if Goldbach's conjecture is false.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-quanta_40-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture#cite_note-quanta-40"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Hence if BB(=
27) was known, and the Turing machine did not stop in that number of steps,=
 it would be known to run forever and hence no counterexamples would exist =
(proving the conjecture). This is a completely impractical way to settle th=
e conjecture; instead it is used to suggest that BB(27) will be very hard t=
o compute, at least as difficult as settling the Goldbach conjecture.
</p>
